===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `linux64` command is used to determine if your Linux system is running a 64-bit architecture. It provides information about both the hardware (CPU) and the kernel to verify 64-bit support.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `linux64 -c`  --> 💻 Checks if the CPU is 64-bit capable.
    🔹 `linux64 -k`  --> ⚙️ Checks if the kernel is running in 64-bit mode.
    🔹 `linux64 -v`  --> ℹ️ Displays the version of the `linux64` utility.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ linux64 -c

    🔹 Checks if the CPU supports 64-bit instructions and prints the result.

    $ linux64 -k

    🔹 Checks if the running kernel is 64-bit and prints the result.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ linux64

    🔹 If the system is 64-bit, it prints "System is 64-bit". Otherwise, it prints "System is not 64-bit".

